WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:17.000
Hello, and with this talk, I want to explore the making of software that feels like magic.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:21.360
And I want to start by reflecting on people's responses to data parser.

00:00:21.360 --> 00:00:26.120
So this is a package that I put on CRAN in 2016, and the community's response to this

00:00:26.120 --> 00:00:29.360
was like beyond anything I ever imagined.

00:00:29.360 --> 00:00:35.660
Lots of kind words in emails and tweets, even at this conference.

00:00:35.660 --> 00:00:41.119
We had some sort of news headline, a crossover with actual parser in a school that I don't

00:00:41.119 --> 00:00:43.919
fully understand.

00:00:43.919 --> 00:00:48.119
And amongst all that, like this little meme emerged.

00:00:48.119 --> 00:00:51.259
And this brings me a lot of joy.

00:00:51.259 --> 00:00:54.320
Even though I've never spoken with anyone about this, it's like somehow I understand

00:00:54.320 --> 00:00:56.099
what's being said here.

00:00:56.099 --> 00:01:03.900
And I've experienced this myself, and I sympathize with this, and, you know, I appreciate this.

00:01:03.900 --> 00:01:06.300
So what is being said?

00:01:06.300 --> 00:01:11.180
I think, you know, the natural definition of magic is like phenomena that violate the

00:01:11.180 --> 00:01:13.660
rules of our world, say.

00:01:13.660 --> 00:01:18.860
I think what's happening here is we're violating people's assumptions about what is within

00:01:18.860 --> 00:01:21.779
their power to do.

00:01:21.800 --> 00:01:26.440
And that is a pretty intoxicating feeling, when you're suddenly shown you have access

00:01:26.440 --> 00:01:28.320
to this power that you didn't realize you had.

00:01:28.320 --> 00:01:32.919
And I think mixed with that is some astonishment and wonder that someone is just handing this

00:01:32.919 --> 00:01:34.919
to you for free.

00:01:34.919 --> 00:01:37.720
So that's what I want to talk about with this talk.

00:01:37.720 --> 00:01:39.080
I want to give you three things.

00:01:39.080 --> 00:01:43.279
So one is, like, the general forms of tools that can do this.

00:01:43.279 --> 00:01:46.879
Two is, like, some ideas about how they do this and how you can do this with the things

00:01:46.879 --> 00:01:48.320
that you work on.

00:01:48.320 --> 00:01:52.419
And three is, like, some broader ideas about, like, how we can make sure we keep seeing

00:01:52.419 --> 00:01:56.379
this type of stuff come out of our community, okay?

00:01:56.379 --> 00:01:59.860
So chapter one, R packages is magic.

00:01:59.860 --> 00:02:01.059
Let's go.

00:02:01.059 --> 00:02:07.540
So this is a monthly plot of the proportion of Rstats tweets that mention magic, witchcraft

00:02:07.540 --> 00:02:09.339
or sorcery.

00:02:09.339 --> 00:02:13.100
And something pretty interesting is happening in 2016, right?

00:02:13.100 --> 00:02:18.100
Like the rate at which people are likening R to magic has accelerated and is continuing

00:02:18.119 --> 00:02:19.600
to accelerate.

00:02:19.600 --> 00:02:23.119
So who has a theory as to what this is due to?

00:02:23.119 --> 00:02:24.119
Yes?

00:02:24.119 --> 00:02:25.119
Tidyverse.

00:02:25.119 --> 00:02:26.119
Yes.

00:02:26.119 --> 00:02:31.240
And we can confirm that by tallying up the mentions of CRAN packages within those tweets

00:02:31.240 --> 00:02:34.440
and you get this distribution of magical mentions.

00:02:34.440 --> 00:02:36.279
And the dark bars are the ones that I think are signal.

00:02:36.279 --> 00:02:39.119
The gray ones are a bit noisy because of their names.

00:02:39.119 --> 00:02:42.399
So yeah, we've got some household names up the top there.

00:02:42.399 --> 00:02:45.500
But this is, like, more or less what I expected to see.

00:02:45.500 --> 00:02:47.500
What I didn't expect was this.

00:02:47.500 --> 00:02:51.720
So we've got a really long tale of magic in our universe.

00:02:51.720 --> 00:02:53.000
And that is intriguing.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:57.119
Because that suggests, like, there's a lot of, like, lesser known stuff out there to

00:02:57.119 --> 00:02:59.119
be discovered.

00:02:59.119 --> 00:03:02.000
So is anyone interested in discovering some of these?

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:03.000
Yeah.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:04.000
Cool.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:06.820
I was banking on that, obviously.

00:03:06.820 --> 00:03:09.639
So what I've done is I've, like, formed them into categories because I think that's the

00:03:09.639 --> 00:03:11.720
only way to sensibly discuss so many.

00:03:11.720 --> 00:03:14.919
I feel like there's probably, like, five or six natural categories and I'm gonna talk

00:03:14.919 --> 00:03:16.380
about three today.

00:03:16.380 --> 00:03:19.119
So the first one is Zaps.

00:03:19.119 --> 00:03:21.960
And they remind me of the way that magic works in Harry Potter.

00:03:21.960 --> 00:03:25.399
Because you have this tool and you have this problem and you point and you say the magic

00:03:25.399 --> 00:03:28.279
word and magic happens and there's a problem that's solved.

00:03:28.279 --> 00:03:32.979
And the magic word might be, like, install tiny tech, in which case the dependencies

00:03:32.979 --> 00:03:37.119
to knit a PDF would just manifest themselves on your computer.

00:03:37.119 --> 00:03:39.639
And that's pretty powerful, like, depending on who you are.

00:03:39.639 --> 00:03:43.360
But the reason I'm showing you this code is because I think this is, like, the template

00:03:43.360 --> 00:03:44.500
for a Zap.

00:03:44.500 --> 00:03:48.479
They often have, like, one hero function that does all the work.

00:03:48.479 --> 00:03:50.440
And they tend to share a name.

00:03:50.440 --> 00:03:52.600
That function will share a name with the package itself.

00:03:52.600 --> 00:03:55.899
So they're very much, like, one function packages.

00:03:55.899 --> 00:03:57.600
This is, like, the largest category.

00:03:57.600 --> 00:03:58.919
A few other interesting things.

00:03:58.919 --> 00:04:01.479
So the most tweeted about was here.

00:04:01.479 --> 00:04:04.440
And I want to give a special mention to Janitor, which, like, although it has many functions,

00:04:04.440 --> 00:04:08.360
I feel like it's like a spell book, if you like, of these little Zaps.

00:04:08.360 --> 00:04:11.460
Some C also is there for you later.

00:04:11.460 --> 00:04:13.160
Now I want to introduce you to genies.

00:04:13.899 --> 00:04:18.779
I call them genies because they convey magic by some kind of interaction with a program.

00:04:18.779 --> 00:04:21.220
And their goal is to assist you to do something.

00:04:21.220 --> 00:04:26.660
So they do this by creating, like, additional UIs with RStudio add-ins or, like, console

00:04:26.660 --> 00:04:27.660
dialogues.

00:04:27.660 --> 00:04:30.500
So they only work in the interactive context.

00:04:30.500 --> 00:04:33.940
And I want to highlight an example called map edit by Tim Appelens.

00:04:33.940 --> 00:04:38.019
And map edit will allow you to, like, draw geometry directly onto a leaflet map and then

00:04:38.019 --> 00:04:44.920
export that back into your R session as a geospatial dataset, which is pretty badass.

00:04:44.920 --> 00:04:47.440
Some C also is there.

00:04:47.440 --> 00:04:50.720
And now the third one that I want to introduce you to is tongues.

00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:51.720
And I don't know if anyone has read this book.

00:04:51.720 --> 00:04:52.720
It's a pretty good book.

00:04:52.720 --> 00:04:57.959
But in this universe, there's a very strong theme of, like, the power of words and in

00:04:57.959 --> 00:05:00.000
particular, like, the power of names.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:01.000
Okay.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:02.000
So that...

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:03.000
Sorry.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:07.359
So much so that if you can discern the true name of something, like, say, the wind, you

00:05:07.359 --> 00:05:09.299
can, like, gain power over it.

00:05:09.299 --> 00:05:10.299
Yeah?

00:05:10.299 --> 00:05:12.779
So that kind of reminds me of what's going on in this universe.

00:05:12.779 --> 00:05:16.739
And I don't think we can, like, understate the contribution of the name tidy data alone.

00:05:16.739 --> 00:05:19.100
Like it's an accessible name.

00:05:19.100 --> 00:05:23.459
We don't have the third normal formally verse, right?

00:05:23.459 --> 00:05:28.420
And that name sets up an intuition that is just confirmed by a definition.

00:05:28.420 --> 00:05:30.579
And that pattern plays out all over the tidyverse.

00:05:30.579 --> 00:05:31.940
It's not all magical.

00:05:31.940 --> 00:05:35.739
But where it is, you can just navigate it with a cheat sheet and autocomplete because

00:05:35.760 --> 00:05:39.640
the names of the functions map so well to the problem domain.

00:05:39.640 --> 00:05:41.679
So this is not, like, unique to the tidyverse.

00:05:41.679 --> 00:05:45.679
I think the general pattern of a tongue is it tries to create, like, a new language for

00:05:45.679 --> 00:05:47.799
you to more easily express and solve a problem.

00:05:47.799 --> 00:05:48.799
Okay?

00:05:48.799 --> 00:05:53.880
So these are, like, three forms of tools that can, you know, create magic for users.

00:05:53.880 --> 00:05:57.519
But what I want to do now is talk about how are they doing this?

00:05:57.519 --> 00:06:00.640
Like, how are they creating this feeling and how can you create it with the things that

00:06:00.640 --> 00:06:02.679
you, like, work on as well?

00:06:02.679 --> 00:06:03.679
Okay.

00:06:03.679 --> 00:06:05.679
So here's, like, an idea.

00:06:05.700 --> 00:06:10.019
Like, talking about expectations being violated, I think we can frame that as, like, maybe

00:06:10.019 --> 00:06:15.260
magic is the appearance of, you know, when you're granted power disproportionately to

00:06:15.260 --> 00:06:19.100
the pain that you're expected to, like, have to go through to get that power.

00:06:19.100 --> 00:06:22.739
I've got the, like, subscript I there because I think it's important to acknowledge that

00:06:22.739 --> 00:06:23.739
this is individual.

00:06:23.739 --> 00:06:26.779
Because people have different skills and experiences, so they're going to see this a little bit

00:06:26.779 --> 00:06:27.779
differently.

00:06:27.779 --> 00:06:32.459
But what I noticed was, like, when I started to look at the packages in this set, like,

00:06:32.459 --> 00:06:34.600
they all grant power, definitely.

00:06:34.600 --> 00:06:39.480
But they seem to, like, invest a whole bunch of, like, dedicated effort into taking away

00:06:39.480 --> 00:06:41.160
user pain.

00:06:41.160 --> 00:06:43.600
And that started me thinking, like, maybe this is, like, it.

00:06:43.600 --> 00:06:45.760
Maybe this is, like, the special thing.

00:06:45.760 --> 00:06:49.519
So I created this little litmus test, and I think this basically holds up.

00:06:49.519 --> 00:06:53.679
I think if you can, like, write this out convincingly for a tool, then there's probably a good chance

00:06:53.679 --> 00:06:57.000
that someone will find that, like, to be magical.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:00.279
And it's a pretty simple, like, test that just goes, like, the magic of tool is that

00:07:00.279 --> 00:07:03.859
it grants you power while saving you from pain, and you put in, like, what it does for

00:07:03.859 --> 00:07:06.820
power and what it, like, saves you from for pain.

00:07:06.820 --> 00:07:09.339
So let's try Deployer.

00:07:09.339 --> 00:07:13.339
Magic of Deployer is that it grants you vocabulary for wrangling data, right?

00:07:13.339 --> 00:07:16.700
Now I haven't told you the pain that it saves you, and because of that, like, Deployer sounds

00:07:16.700 --> 00:07:17.700
a bit flat.

00:07:17.700 --> 00:07:20.459
Like, base R can do this, right?

00:07:20.459 --> 00:07:24.899
Well, the magic of Deployer, sorry, is that it saves you from, like, mindless typing because

00:07:24.899 --> 00:07:28.820
of the pipeable interface and nonstandard evaluation, saves you from, like, having to

00:07:28.820 --> 00:07:31.079
read because the functions are so well-named.

00:07:31.079 --> 00:07:35.440
It saves you from having to learn SQL because it will write that to a database for you,

00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:37.239
and that is pretty awesome.

00:07:37.239 --> 00:07:38.239
So let's go to TinyTech now.

00:07:38.239 --> 00:07:42.559
The magic of TinyTech is that it grants you the things you need to need a PDF while saving

00:07:42.559 --> 00:07:48.619
you from, like, bloated 4 gigabyte downloads, navigating, you know, ancient websites and

00:07:48.619 --> 00:07:50.119
reading horrible instructions.

00:07:50.119 --> 00:07:54.679
There's a catalog of user pain associated with setting up a LaTeX environment, and the

00:07:54.679 --> 00:07:58.720
author of this package has, like, documented it all in this neat page.

00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:03.179
I think the link to this page is even called, like, the hall of pain.

00:08:03.179 --> 00:08:05.980
So this is a really interesting thing to read, like, if you want to get insight into, like,

00:08:05.980 --> 00:08:10.100
the mind of someone who is really, like, in tune with user pain, like, it consistently

00:08:10.100 --> 00:08:14.380
creates things that people perceive to be magical.

00:08:14.380 --> 00:08:17.940
So the real value of this little thing, though, I think, is that you can flip it and it can

00:08:17.940 --> 00:08:19.480
be a design tool.

00:08:19.480 --> 00:08:23.579
So if you're working on something that you want to imbue with more magic, like, I think

00:08:23.579 --> 00:08:28.179
you just have to, like, shove as much stuff into that last section as possible, right?

00:08:28.179 --> 00:08:31.519
But you need some ideas of, like, what you're going to do.

00:08:31.519 --> 00:08:36.000
So obviously one place to start is, like, what are my pain points when I'm doing my

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:37.000
own R analysis?

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:38.000
And I don't know yours, right?

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:39.000
But I know mine.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:41.280
I can tell you my top three.

00:08:41.280 --> 00:08:45.599
So I hate mindless typing, and that's, like, typing where I know what I've got to type

00:08:45.599 --> 00:08:49.640
and I'm just, like, waiting for my fingers to finish this verbose, like, thing.

00:08:49.640 --> 00:08:51.039
I hate reading code.

00:08:51.039 --> 00:08:53.320
I hate reading about code.

00:08:53.320 --> 00:08:56.640
And I hate making decisions about code.

00:08:56.640 --> 00:09:00.500
Because all these things, like, take my mind off the analysis that I'm trying to do and,

00:09:00.500 --> 00:09:05.059
like, put me into this, like, code world where, like, often I prefer not to be, like, well,

00:09:05.059 --> 00:09:09.179
at least, like, maybe not without my consent anyway, right?

00:09:09.179 --> 00:09:11.539
So those are a bit abstract.

00:09:11.539 --> 00:09:14.919
Like let's think about some concrete ways you could, like, implement these.

00:09:14.919 --> 00:09:17.000
So saving typing, like, here's the continuum.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:20.380
You could, like, do the pipeable functions with the nonstandard evaluation.

00:09:20.380 --> 00:09:24.700
You could use the autocomplete friendly names to, like, you know, only type part of it.

00:09:24.700 --> 00:09:26.500
Or you could take the typing away completely.

00:09:26.500 --> 00:09:28.119
And that's what I did with data pasta.

00:09:28.119 --> 00:09:32.799
I really tried to bank heavily on that for magic and drill into, like, minimizing the

00:09:32.799 --> 00:09:35.000
keystrokes to the absolute.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:39.400
So you can kind of guess from that how much I hate typing.

00:09:39.400 --> 00:09:43.840
And saving reading, well, we've talked about the intuitive names.

00:09:43.840 --> 00:09:48.280
Conforming becomes really important when you are making a model or a method, right?

00:09:48.280 --> 00:09:51.400
Because what your users fundamentally want to do with a model or a method is compare

00:09:51.400 --> 00:09:54.200
it to one they actually understand, yeah?

00:09:54.200 --> 00:09:57.179
And to do that, it needs to have, like, it needs to look a certain way.

00:09:57.179 --> 00:10:02.140
Like, it needs to take a data frame, use a formula interface and return an object that

00:10:02.140 --> 00:10:04.179
implements certain S3 methods.

00:10:04.179 --> 00:10:07.659
And if it doesn't do that, like, you're just foisting a whole bunch of reading and learning

00:10:07.659 --> 00:10:12.380
onto your user to allow them to make the comparison that you know they want to make.

00:10:12.380 --> 00:10:13.940
So don't do that.

00:10:13.940 --> 00:10:14.940
Conform.

00:10:14.940 --> 00:10:16.380
Also be flexible.

00:10:16.380 --> 00:10:20.900
So I think potentially the worst kind of reading you can do is, like, reading error messages

00:10:20.900 --> 00:10:24.960
and then reading stack overflow pages, trying to resolve those, right?

00:10:24.960 --> 00:10:27.359
So actually base R is really good at this.

00:10:27.359 --> 00:10:31.440
Base R will happily convert between lists and vectors and matrices and data frames and

00:10:31.440 --> 00:10:33.239
all different types of objects.

00:10:33.239 --> 00:10:38.080
So if you create an interface which is very rigid by comparison to base R, it's going

00:10:38.080 --> 00:10:41.239
to feel really nonmagical to people.

00:10:41.239 --> 00:10:46.320
Finally, this is probably one of the key categories.

00:10:46.320 --> 00:10:50.940
Making people decisions is a really easy way to, like, make them happy.

00:10:50.940 --> 00:10:54.619
So defaults are a way to do that, but I've had this interesting conversation with people

00:10:54.619 --> 00:10:58.619
about defaults a number of times over the last year where I've got this counter argument

00:10:58.619 --> 00:11:00.859
to defaults, and I want to share it with you.

00:11:00.859 --> 00:11:08.200
So the argument goes, so I could use a default here, but I'm worried that my user will blindly

00:11:08.200 --> 00:11:14.419
use that default, arrive at an invalid answer, and then blindly use that answer, okay?

00:11:14.419 --> 00:11:18.559
So I guess, like, my rebuttal to this is, like, why does your tool give answers that

00:11:18.559 --> 00:11:21.919
users can't, like, discern the validity of, you know?

00:11:21.919 --> 00:11:26.760
So could you potentially invest in some diagnostics or some things for your users to, you know,

00:11:26.760 --> 00:11:28.200
be able to tell if the answer is right?

00:11:28.200 --> 00:11:31.760
And if you did that, you know, you've got, like, pain being saved on the sad path where

00:11:31.760 --> 00:11:35.200
there's no default and pain being saved on the happy path, you know, because you've got

00:11:35.200 --> 00:11:39.520
the default and you've just got a more magical thing overall.

00:11:39.520 --> 00:11:41.400
In the middle there I just want to cite two examples.

00:11:41.400 --> 00:11:46.619
So there's no way I would have released data pasta were it not for, like, DevTools and

00:11:46.619 --> 00:11:47.619
R hub.

00:11:47.619 --> 00:11:51.940
So these packages, I see Jim and Gabor in the front there.

00:11:51.940 --> 00:11:57.659
So these packages help you navigate, like, the rat run of releasing an R package.

00:11:57.659 --> 00:12:00.780
Like they give you little dialogues that make you, like, help you think about the right

00:12:00.780 --> 00:12:01.780
thing at the right time.

00:12:01.780 --> 00:12:04.099
So that's something that you could emulate.

00:12:04.099 --> 00:12:09.419
And finally I think, like, this applies to all tools, like, just give people less choices.

00:12:09.440 --> 00:12:13.559
Because for a user to, like, make a confident decision, they have to kind of pause this

00:12:13.559 --> 00:12:14.559
choice space.

00:12:14.559 --> 00:12:18.320
And the more things you're, like, tossing in there, like, the bigger this space is growing

00:12:18.320 --> 00:12:21.159
and the more I have to try and understand to, like, be confident.

00:12:21.159 --> 00:12:24.159
So you're actually just creating anxiety for me, you know?

00:12:24.159 --> 00:12:28.960
So shrink that down, reduce my anxiety, curate your experience, and I think, like, that will

00:12:28.960 --> 00:12:31.799
definitely make something more magical.

00:12:31.799 --> 00:12:35.719
So those are, like, three pain points and then, like, three ideas about how to address

00:12:35.719 --> 00:12:36.719
those.

00:12:36.719 --> 00:12:39.020
And I know you have your own pain points and your own ideas and, like, I'm really here

00:12:39.020 --> 00:12:40.020
for that conversation.

00:12:40.020 --> 00:12:43.659
But I just want to switch up now to something a bit more important.

00:12:43.659 --> 00:12:48.859
Which is, like, how can we make sure we keep seeing more of this come out of our community?

00:12:48.859 --> 00:12:49.859
Okay.

00:12:49.859 --> 00:12:53.640
So I think there's, like, a segment of our community that is really in tune with user

00:12:53.640 --> 00:12:57.340
pain and we should listen to them and we should learn from them.

00:12:57.340 --> 00:13:00.020
And that's these people in the red zone.

00:13:00.020 --> 00:13:03.340
So these people are not professional software developers.

00:13:03.340 --> 00:13:06.719
They are amateur software developers, but they're professional analysts and they're

00:13:06.719 --> 00:13:08.400
professional scientists.

00:13:08.400 --> 00:13:11.440
And they are, like, living the pain every day of, like, having a problem and having

00:13:11.440 --> 00:13:14.960
a tool and having those not quite meet.

00:13:14.960 --> 00:13:19.520
I think it will be their insights into those gaps that will spawn, like, the next wave

00:13:19.520 --> 00:13:21.200
of magical tools.

00:13:21.200 --> 00:13:25.559
And that has the capacity to become, like, a virtuous cycle when those tools attract

00:13:25.559 --> 00:13:28.479
new users to our community, right?

00:13:28.479 --> 00:13:31.679
And it's worth thinking about, like, amateurs have already created a bunch of cool stuff

00:13:31.679 --> 00:13:32.679
for us.

00:13:33.020 --> 00:13:37.659
Like, DataPasta, obviously written by a total amateur, but on a more significant level,

00:13:37.659 --> 00:13:43.179
we've got Knitter and GigiPlot and Sybil now, you know, chamber award winning package.

00:13:43.179 --> 00:13:47.979
These are all created by students, right?

00:13:47.979 --> 00:13:51.940
Were they wasting their time writing R packages instead of working on their thesis?

00:13:51.940 --> 00:13:52.940
No.

00:13:52.940 --> 00:13:55.659
Like, that's garbage, right?

00:13:55.659 --> 00:13:59.299
So what I want to do now is, like, for anyone who is, like, on the cusp of, like, committing

00:13:59.299 --> 00:14:03.280
to, like, developing a tool that might take away some pain, I want to, like, dispel a

00:14:03.280 --> 00:14:06.359
few myths for you that might, like, get you over the line.

00:14:06.359 --> 00:14:07.359
I don't know.

00:14:07.359 --> 00:14:10.520
So the first myth I want to dispel is that for a tool to be magical, it needs, like,

00:14:10.520 --> 00:14:12.280
a grand vision, right?

00:14:12.280 --> 00:14:16.479
So say, like, GigiPlot is, like, going to change the way you express graphics.

00:14:16.479 --> 00:14:17.479
Okay.

00:14:17.479 --> 00:14:22.159
But DataPasta is going to help you move text from this window to this window on your screen.

00:14:22.159 --> 00:14:26.599
And something like Glue is going to, like, reduce the code you write and make that code

00:14:26.599 --> 00:14:31.419
more readable so long as that code is for string concatenation, you know?

00:14:31.419 --> 00:14:33.940
But I'm an ex-heavy paste user.

00:14:33.940 --> 00:14:39.780
I use Glue all the time, and every time I do, like, I get a warm, fuzzy feeling.

00:14:39.780 --> 00:14:40.780
So that's busted.

00:14:40.780 --> 00:14:44.900
Now, the second myth I want to bust is that magical code needs to smell good.

00:14:44.900 --> 00:14:49.659
And here I'm referencing Jenny Brian's amazing talk, code smells and feels.

00:14:49.659 --> 00:14:55.020
And in this slide of that talk, Jenny is discussing how the level of indentation and nesting can

00:14:55.020 --> 00:14:58.119
be used as a metric to identify code that can be refactored.

00:14:58.119 --> 00:15:01.320
So going from something on the left to something on the right.

00:15:01.320 --> 00:15:02.320
Yeah, cool.

00:15:02.320 --> 00:15:06.320
So here's DataPasta.

00:15:06.320 --> 00:15:08.960
And look at all that paste, paste, paste.

00:15:08.960 --> 00:15:12.679
Yeah, so, like, this is a little bit scary to me.

00:15:12.679 --> 00:15:17.280
I do feel, like, some pressure to rewrite this, but at the same time, like, I'm a little

00:15:17.280 --> 00:15:21.440
bit scared that I don't fully understand what's going on here anymore.

00:15:21.440 --> 00:15:24.039
And actually, I don't mind having this, like, around.

00:15:24.059 --> 00:15:26.179
This is, like, nostalgia for me.

00:15:26.179 --> 00:15:30.340
This is what I thought writing R code was only three years ago.

00:15:30.340 --> 00:15:32.940
So I've come a fairly long way since then.

00:15:32.940 --> 00:15:37.260
So it's nice to have this touchstone, and, you know, it helps to be in good company.

00:15:37.260 --> 00:15:41.340
So this is one of the most magical functions on CRAN.

00:15:41.340 --> 00:15:42.340
There's some hints in there.

00:15:42.340 --> 00:15:44.340
Can anyone pick it?

00:15:44.340 --> 00:15:46.900
Yes.

00:15:46.900 --> 00:15:49.859
So this is auto.arima from forecast.

00:15:49.859 --> 00:15:52.979
And you just kind of, like, fling at a time series, and it will catch it and churn away

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:57.359
and give you back the best model that it can, which is really awesome.

00:15:57.359 --> 00:15:59.919
But yeah, there's a bit going on there.

00:15:59.919 --> 00:16:03.440
So if this is good enough for Rob Heinman, and this is good enough for me, it's good

00:16:03.440 --> 00:16:08.840
enough for you, and, like, the properties of your code in no way correlate to the amount

00:16:08.840 --> 00:16:11.039
of magic that it can make someone feel.

00:16:11.039 --> 00:16:15.919
In fact, it might even anti-correlate, but that's another story.

00:16:15.919 --> 00:16:18.239
So now I want to make an observation, right?

00:16:18.239 --> 00:16:21.719
I think it would be really cool if we had, like, an organization in our community that

00:16:21.739 --> 00:16:26.299
was dedicated to, like, welcoming amateurs and making them, like, empowering them to

00:16:26.299 --> 00:16:28.099
become toolmakers, right?

00:16:28.099 --> 00:16:32.260
So we need a forum and a website, of course, and that's all, like, details, details.

00:16:32.260 --> 00:16:36.780
But what I want to discuss right now is, like, the important issue of, like, the logo that

00:16:36.780 --> 00:16:38.419
we'd use for our hex sticker, right?

00:16:38.419 --> 00:16:39.419
Yeah.

00:16:39.419 --> 00:16:40.419
Very important.

00:16:40.419 --> 00:16:41.979
So I want to propose this motif.

00:16:41.979 --> 00:16:44.460
This has been my progress tracker up until now.

00:16:44.460 --> 00:16:49.739
But it's also a mana orb, and a mana orb, like, represents a pool of magical energy

00:16:49.840 --> 00:16:53.239
in, like, computer games and video games and stuff like that, right?

00:16:53.239 --> 00:16:57.640
So we're an R community, so we drop an R on that.

00:16:57.640 --> 00:17:03.159
And it's, like, someone already had this idea, right?

00:17:03.159 --> 00:17:06.880
And, like, they're doing an all right job, so we'll let them keep running with that.

00:17:06.880 --> 00:17:10.040
But the reason that I'm showing you this is because, like, I don't know if this is a coincidence.

00:17:10.040 --> 00:17:12.359
Just, like, I don't know if this is a coincidence.

00:17:12.359 --> 00:17:17.599
This is, like, this is the first RStudioConf at Harry Potter World, you know?

00:17:18.020 --> 00:17:21.459
And it's, like, maybe there's something embedded in our collective understanding of what we're

00:17:21.459 --> 00:17:22.459
doing here.

00:17:22.459 --> 00:17:23.459
I don't know.

00:17:23.459 --> 00:17:26.300
I've got some more examples that I might blog or tweet or something.

00:17:26.300 --> 00:17:27.300
But yeah.

00:17:27.300 --> 00:17:28.300
I'll leave that with you.

00:17:28.300 --> 00:17:30.579
I'm gonna wrap up my talk now.

00:17:30.579 --> 00:17:33.420
So this is basically my idea.

00:17:33.420 --> 00:17:36.060
There are two ways to create software that feels like magic.

00:17:36.060 --> 00:17:37.939
Number one is, like, directly.

00:17:37.939 --> 00:17:43.420
And you can, you know, create something that passes this test, take away user pain.

00:17:43.420 --> 00:17:46.119
And number two is indirectly.

00:17:46.140 --> 00:17:50.660
And you do that by supporting these people, our amateurs, you know, listening to them

00:17:50.660 --> 00:17:53.140
and empowering them to become toolmakers.

00:17:53.140 --> 00:17:55.300
So that's my talk.

00:17:55.300 --> 00:17:57.300
Thanks very much for listening.

00:17:57.300 --> 00:17:58.300
Yeah.

00:17:58.300 --> 00:17:59.300
Well...

00:17:59.300 --> 00:18:10.219
Thank you very much, Miles, for that wonderful talk.

00:18:10.219 --> 00:18:15.040
The magic of this talk, of course, was it gave excellent insights and saved me from

00:18:15.040 --> 00:18:18.979
trawling 14,000 packages to do this work myself.

00:18:18.979 --> 00:18:21.739
So we have two or three minutes for questions.

00:18:21.739 --> 00:18:25.459
There's a gentleman with a black shirt over there.

00:18:25.459 --> 00:18:31.300
Hi, great talk.

00:18:31.300 --> 00:18:39.339
So I feel like the distinction between creating magic and then someone calling it API obfuscation,

00:18:39.339 --> 00:18:44.180
I feel like is drawn between how much trust they have, right?

00:18:44.180 --> 00:18:46.660
In what you're doing and the functions that you're building, right?

00:18:46.660 --> 00:18:53.939
And so as a student, right, developing a package, how do I build that trust in the work that

00:18:53.939 --> 00:19:00.500
I do and, you know, make it so it's people can use it and have trust in that what's working

00:19:00.500 --> 00:19:03.099
on the back end is reliable and safe?

00:19:03.099 --> 00:19:04.099
Yeah.

00:19:04.099 --> 00:19:05.099
Okay.

00:19:05.099 --> 00:19:06.099
That's a really good question.

00:19:06.099 --> 00:19:10.780
So if you develop something magical and no one ever uses it, I guess that's going to

00:19:10.780 --> 00:19:11.780
be a real shame.

00:19:11.780 --> 00:19:16.099
I mean, I can't really give heaps of advice.

00:19:16.099 --> 00:19:20.540
When I created Datapaster, I mean, the thing that got Datapaster off the ground really

00:19:20.540 --> 00:19:21.540
was that GIF.

00:19:21.540 --> 00:19:27.739
I tweeted that GIF, and that just sort of went viral from there, and I think the use

00:19:27.739 --> 00:19:34.900
case was so compelling that, like, the trust issue wasn't, like, what's the cost here?

00:19:34.900 --> 00:19:35.900
You know?

00:19:35.900 --> 00:19:40.500
Like, if this doesn't work for you, and often Datapaster doesn't work for people, but, like,

00:19:40.500 --> 00:19:41.500
you've lost nothing, really.

00:19:41.500 --> 00:19:44.579
You've lost a couple of minutes, and you'll go back and you'll do this the normal way.

00:19:44.579 --> 00:19:48.099
But if this does work, like, it saved you a whole bunch of time.

00:19:48.099 --> 00:19:52.780
So I think it's a combination of, like, making a compelling case and also, like, putting

00:19:52.780 --> 00:19:53.780
it out there.

00:19:53.780 --> 00:19:54.780
Yeah?

00:19:54.780 --> 00:19:55.780
Okay.

00:19:55.780 --> 00:19:56.780
Another question?

00:19:56.780 --> 00:19:57.780
Any other questions?

00:19:57.780 --> 00:19:58.780
There's one over here.

00:19:58.780 --> 00:20:03.739
Any other questions?

00:20:03.739 --> 00:20:04.739
Any other questions?

00:20:04.739 --> 00:20:07.939
There's, at the back, Jack Shirt.

00:20:07.939 --> 00:20:08.939
Thank you.

00:20:08.939 --> 00:20:09.939
Hi.

00:20:09.939 --> 00:20:10.939
Hi.

00:20:10.939 --> 00:20:16.260
So sometimes in software development, deep magic or dark magic is kind of a pejorative.

00:20:16.260 --> 00:20:17.260
Yeah.

00:20:17.260 --> 00:20:18.260
Right?

00:20:18.260 --> 00:20:21.579
So I'm wondering about, you know, you're talking about reducing user options, and I think that's

00:20:21.579 --> 00:20:26.140
generally a good idea, but one of the worst experiences is when the magic kind of runs

00:20:26.140 --> 00:20:29.939
out and you find out that the tool can't do the thing you want to do.

00:20:29.939 --> 00:20:35.219
So I'm wondering how you think about balancing kind of exposing some of the deeper workings

00:20:35.219 --> 00:20:40.579
of a thing and allowing people to go deep when they need to.

00:20:40.579 --> 00:20:41.579
Yeah.

00:20:41.579 --> 00:20:47.339
I mean, I actually think you just have to really be led by your users and listen to

00:20:47.339 --> 00:20:48.339
them.

00:20:48.339 --> 00:20:53.060
And so, like, I wouldn't, like, put those options in speculatively, but I guess I would

00:20:53.060 --> 00:20:57.859
try to be really responsive and listen to what people want, you know, and listen to

00:20:57.859 --> 00:21:02.900
the issues that are coming up on my GitHub and people are tweeting about.

00:21:02.900 --> 00:21:10.099
So I guess just in time magic, maybe.

